 and Income Taxes [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/335]||align=\"center\" |1952 November\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |43||Restatement and Revision of Accounting Research Bulletins [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/336]||align=\"center\" |1953\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |44||Declining-Balance Depreciation  [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/337]||align=\"center\" |1954 October\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |44 Revised||Declining-Balance Depreciation (Supersedes Accounting Research Bulletin No. 44 issued in October 1954) [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/338]||align=\"center\" |1958 July\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |45||Long-term Construction-type Contracts [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/339]||align=\"center\" |1955 October\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |46||Discontinuance of Dating Earned Surplus [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/340]||align=\"center\" |1956 February\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |47||Accounting for costs of Pension Plans [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/341]||align=\"center\" |1956 September\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |48||Business Combinations (Supersedes chapter 7(c) of Accounting Research Bulletin No. 43) [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/342]||align=\"center\" |1957 January\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |49||Earnings per Share [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/343]||align=\"center\" |1958 April\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |50||Contingencies [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/345]||align=\"center\" |1958 October\n|-\n|align=\"center\" |51||Consolidated Financial Statements [https://egrove.olemiss.edu/dl_aia/346]||align=\"center\" |1959 August\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Accounting in the United States]]\n[[Category:Accounting research]]\n", "name_user": "Pol098", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accounting_Research_Bulletins"}
{"title_page": "Hutki Shira", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Fermented fish curry}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             =  Hutki Shira\n| image            =  \ua816\ua826\ua81e\ua826\ua821\ua827\ua81e \ua822\ua825\ua810\ua807\ua824 \ua821\ua824\ua81e\ua823.jpg\n| caption          = Okra Hutki Shira \n| alternate_name   = Hukoin Shira\n| region            = [[Sylhet]]\n| country          = {{flag|Bangladesh}}\n| course           = Main course\n| type             = [[Curry]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = Hidol [[Hutki]], [[garlic]], [[turmeric]] and any seasonal [[vegetables]].\n| variations       = \n| other            =\n}}\n'''Hutki Shira''' ({{lang-syl|\ua822\ua825\ua810\ua807\ua824 \ua821\ua824\ua81e\ua823}}, {{lang-bn|\u09b6\u09c1\u099f\u0995\u09bf \u09b6\u09bf\u09b0\u09be|Shutki Shira}}) is a [[fermented fish]] curry made of vegetables, leafy greens and [[fish]] or [[prawns]].<ref name=afk>{{citenews|url=https://www.afeliaskitchen.com/mukhir-hutki-shira/|title=Mukhir Hutki Shira|access-date=20 April 2020| date=11 Feb 2017| publisher=Afelia's Kitchen}}</ref> It is cooked without [[oil]] or fat, only the seasonal vegetables is used, such as [[gourd]] leaf, [[eggplant]] etc.<ref>{{citenews|url=http://www.abasar.net/souranshu_Sihleti.htm|title=\u09ab\u09bf\u09b8\u09ab\u09be\u09b8 \u0995\u09bf\u099a\u09c7\u09a8- \u09b8\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u099f\u09c0 \u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be- \u09ac\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u09a4\u09bf \u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be|access-date=22 April 2020| date=30 Sep 2016| publisher=www.abasar.net}}</ref> \n<ref>{{citenews|url=http://www.homechef.com.bd/recipe/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%9F%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%B6%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A8%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE--by-homefood|title=\u09b6\u09c1\u099f\u0995\u09bf \u09b6\u09bf\u09b0\u09be (\u09b8\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u099f\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be)|language=bn |access-date=22 April 2020| date=13 Mar 2019| publisher=www.homechef.com.bd}}</ref>  It\u2019s a very famous dish in [[Sylhet region]] with many variations.<ref name=gbc>{{citenews|url=https://www.greatbritishchefs.com/recipes/shutki-shira-recipe|title=Shutki shira \u2013 Bangladeshi dried shrimp stew|access-date=20 April 2020| date=| publisher=[[Great British Chefs]]}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nAny fermented fish is called Hutki in [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]], it is spelled Shutki in [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref name=gbc1>{{citenews|url=https://www.greatbritishchefs.com/features/bangladeshi-food-guide-cuisine|title=The 6 Seasons of Bangladeshi Cuisine|access-date=22 April 2020| date=8 March 2019| publisher=Great British Chefs}}</ref> Shira ({{lang-bn|Jhool}}) describes broth. Thus, Hutki Shira means the broth of fermented fish.\n\n\n== Variations ==\nHutki Shira is of different kinds depending on seasonal vegetables such as ''Lotar Hutki Shira'', ''Radish hutki shira'' or ''Aubergine hutki Shira'', ''Eddoe Hutki Shira'' etc.<ref name=afk/>\n=== Mukhir Hutki Shira ===\n[[Eddoe]] is known as Mukhi in Bengali. From where this particular recipe got the name as Mukhir Hutki Shira.<ref name=afk/> Traditionally Hidol is used. But lack of Hidol, Lotia can be used too.\n== Ingredients ==\n''Hidol Hutki'', garlic (crushed), onion (blended), [[potatoes]], [[spinach]], [[aubergine]], [[red pepper]], boiled water, [[chilli powder]], [[salt]] and turmeric.<ref>{{citenews|url=https://www.indiansimmer.com/2016/03/hutki-shira.html|title=Hutki Shira|access-date=22 April 2020| date= 18 Mar 2016| publisher=www.indiansimmer.com}}</ref> \n\n== Process ==\nFirst, the fermented fish is soaked in cold water. Onion, garlic, ground spices, salt and shrimp are put on the pan. Placing a lid on, it\u2019s cooked for a while over a high heat. Keeping on a high heat, the stuff is stirred several times. Pumpkin and aubergine are added then. Filling the pot with water, cooking is done for a few minutes. At last Naga chilli is added giving the broth a gentle stir.\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{Lists of prepared foods}}\n{{Sylhet topics}}\n\n\n[[Category:Sylheti cuisine]]\n[[Category:Curry dishes]]\n[[Category:Fermented fish]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Fermented fish curry}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             =  Hutki Shira\n| image            =  \ua816\ua826\ua81e\ua826\ua821\ua827\ua81e \ua822\ua825\ua810\ua807\ua824 \ua821\ua824\ua81e\ua823.jpg\n| caption          = Okra Hutki Shira \n| alternate_name   = Hukoin Shira\n| region            = [[Sylhet]]\n| country          = {{flag|Bangladesh}}\n| course           = Main course\n| type             = [[Curry]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = Hidol [[Hutki]], [[garlic]], [[turmeric]] and any seasonal [[vegetables]].\n| variations       = \n| other            =\n}}\n'''Hutki Shira''' ({{lang-syl|\ua822\ua825\ua810\ua807\ua824 \ua821\ua824\ua81e\ua823}}, {{lang-bn|\u09b6\u09c1\u099f\u0995\u09bf \u09b6\u09bf\u09b0\u09be|Shutki Shira}}) is a [[fermented fish]] curry made of vegetables, leafy greens and [[fish]] or [[prawns]].<ref name=afk>{{citenews|url=https://www.afeliaskitchen.com/mukhir-hutki-shira/|title=Mukhir Hutki Shira|access-date=20 April 2020| date=11 Feb 2017| publisher=Afelia's Kitchen}}</ref> It is cooked without [[oil]] or fat, only the seasonal vegetables is used, such as [[gourd]] leaf, [[eggplant]] etc.<ref>{{citenews|url=http://www.abasar.net/souranshu_Sihleti.htm|title=\u09ab\u09bf\u09b8\u09ab\u09be\u09b8 \u0995\u09bf\u099a\u09c7\u09a8- \u09b8\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u099f\u09c0 \u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be- \u09ac\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u09a4\u09bf \u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be|access-date=22 April 2020| date=30 Sep 2016| publisher=www.abasar.net}}</ref> \n<ref>{{citenews|url=http://www.homechef.com.bd/recipe/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%9F%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%B6%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A8%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE--by-homefood|title=\u09b6\u09c1\u099f\u0995\u09bf \u09b6\u09bf\u09b0\u09be (\u09b8\u09bf\u09b2\u09c7\u099f\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be)|language=bn |access-date=22 April 2020| date=13 Mar 2019| publisher=www.homechef.com.bd}}</ref>  It\u2019s a very famous dish in [[Sylhet region]] with many variations.<ref name=gbc>{{citenews|url=https://www.greatbritishchefs.com/recipes/shutki-shira-recipe|title=Shutki shira \u2013 Bangladeshi dried shrimp stew|access-date=20 April 2020| date=| publisher=[[Great British Chefs]]}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nAny fermented fish is called Hutki in [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]], it is spelled Shutki in [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref name=gbc1>{{citenews|url=https://www.greatbritishchefs.com/features/bangladeshi-food-guide-cuisine|title=The 6 Seasons of Bangladeshi Cuisine|access-date=22 April 2020| date=8 March 2019| publisher=Great British Chefs}}</ref> Shira ({{lang-bn|Jhool}}) describes broth. Thus, Hutki Shira means the broth of fermented fish.\n== Etymology ==\nAny fermented fish is called Hutki in [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]] and Shutki in [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref name=gbc1>{{citenews|url=https://www.greatbritishchefs.com/features/bangladeshi-food-guide-cuisine|title=The 6 Seasons of Bangladeshi Cuisine|access-date=22 April 2020| date=8 March 2019| publisher=Great British Chefs}}</ref> Shira ({{lang-bn|Jhool}}) describes broth. Thus, Hutki Shira means the broth of fermented fish.\n\n== Variations ==\nHutki Shira is of different kinds depending on seasonal vegetables such as ''Lotar Hutki Shira'', ''Radish hutki shira'' or ''Aubergine hutki Shira'', ''Eddoe Hutki Shira'' etc.<ref name=afk/>\n=== Mukhir Hutki Shira ===\n[[Eddoe]] is known as Mukhi in Bengali. From where this particular recipe got the name as Mukhir Hutki Shira.<ref name=afk/> Traditionally Hidol is used. But lack of Hidol, Lotia can be used too.\n== Ingredients ==\n''Hidol Hutki'', garlic (crushed), onion (blended), [[potatoes]], [[spinach]], [[aubergine]], [[red pepper]], boiled water, [[chilli powder]], [[salt]] and turmeric.<ref>{{citenews|url=https://www.indiansimmer.com/2016/03/hutki-shira.html|title=Hutki Shira|access-date=22 April 2020| date= 18 Mar 2016| publisher=www.indiansimmer.com}}</ref> \n\n== Process ==\nFirst, the fermented fish is soaked in cold water. Onion, garlic, ground spices, salt and shrimp are put on the pan. Placing a lid on, it\u2019s cooked for a while over a high heat. Keeping on a high heat, the stuff is stirred several times. Pumpkin and aubergine are added then. Filling the pot with water, cooking is done for a few minutes. At last Naga chilli is added giving the broth a gentle stir.\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{Lists of prepared foods}}\n{{Sylhet topics}}\n\n\n[[Category:Sylheti cuisine]]\n[[Category:Curry dishes]]\n[[Category:Fermented fish]]\n", "name_user": "Circular Potato", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted duplicate section.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hutki_Shira"}
{"title_page": "Dinos", "text_new": "{{for|\"dinos\" as the plural of \"dino\"|dinosaur}}\n[[File:Dinos animals Louvre Cp11243.jpg|thumb|Attic ''dinos'', ca. 540 BC, [[Louvre]] Cp 11243]]\nIn the [[Typology of Greek vase shapes|typology of ancient Greek pottery]], the '''''dinos''''' (plural ''dinoi'') is a mixing bowl or cauldron. ''Dinos'' means \"drinking cup,\" but in modern typology is used (wrongly) for the same shape as a ''[[lebes]]'', that is, a bowl with a spherical body meant to sit on a stand. It has no handles and no feet.<ref>Brian A. Sparkes, ''Greek Pottery: An Introduction'' (Manchester University Press, 1991), pp. 62, 81, 83.</ref>\n\nThe [[Dinos Painter]], one of the ancient Greek artists known for [[Pottery of ancient Greece|vase painting]], takes his name from the type of vase characteristic of his work.<ref>Sparkes, ''Greek Pottery'', p. 115.</ref>\n\nDinos were used for mixing water and wine, as it was considered rude to drink straight out of the goblet, at the time.\n\nDinos are still walking the earth today as birds and reptiles many people say there are no more dinos but there are still birds and reptiles and they are scientifically proven to be dinos\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dinos of the Gorgon Painter]]\n* [[Ancient Greek vase painting]]\n* [[Pottery of ancient Greece]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Greek vase shapes}}\n[[Category:Ancient Greek pot shapes]]\n\n\n{{Greece-archaeology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|\"dinos\" as the plural of \"dino\"|dinosaur}}\n[[File:Dinos animals Louvre Cp11243.jpg|thumb|Attic ''dinos'', ca. 540 BC, [[Louvre]] Cp 11243]]\nIn the [[Typology of Greek vase shapes|typology of ancient Greek pottery]], the '''''dinos''''' (plural ''dinoi'') is a mixing bowl or cauldron. ''Dinos'' means \"drinking cup,\" but in modern typology is used (wrongly) for the same shape as a ''[[lebes]]'', that is, a bowl with a spherical body meant to sit on a stand. It has no handles and no feet.<ref>Brian A. Sparkes, ''Greek Pottery: An Introduction'' (Manchester University Press, 1991), pp. 62, 81, 83.</ref>\n\nThe [[Dinos Painter]], one of the ancient Greek artists known for [[Pottery of ancient Greece|vase painting]], takes his name from the type of vase characteristic of his work.<ref>Sparkes, ''Greek Pottery'', p. 115.</ref>\n\nDinos were used for mixing water and wine, as it was considered rude to drink straight out of the goblet, at the time.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dinos of the Gorgon Painter]]\n* [[Ancient Greek vase painting]]\n* [[Pottery of ancient Greece]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Greek vase shapes}}\n[[Category:Ancient Greek pot shapes]]\n\n\n{{Greece-archaeology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DragonBreath109", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I put extra facts that were not included in this)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dinos"}
